value.value: A non-Hodgkin lymphoma that arises from the central nervous system.
A term that refers to high grade B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified or high grade B-cell lymphoma with MYC and BCL2 and/or BCL6 rearrangements.

A partial or complete replacement of the bone marrow stroma by fibrous tissue. It can be a primary bone marrow lesion as part of the chronic myeloproliferative disorders (chronic idiopathic myelofibrosis), a manifestation of acute myeloid leukemia (acute panmyelosis with myelofibrosis), or a secondary phenomenon due to bone marrow involvement by a metastatic tumor (e.g., metastatic breast carcinoma). --2003

A benign neoplasm of the bladder that involves the transitional epithelium projecting above the surrounding epithelial surface and consisting of villous or arborescent outgrowths of fibrovascular stroma.
A squamous cell carcinoma which has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.

label.value: metastatic malignant neoplasm in the spinal cord

value.value: A malignant neoplasm that has spread to the spinal cord from another anatomic site or system. Representative examples include carcinoma, lymphoma, and melanoma.

label.value: metastatic malignant neoplasm in the eye

value.value: A malignant neoplasm that has spread to the eye from another anatomic site.

An aggressive, high grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands. It usually affects elderly males and presents as a rapidly enlarging mass. It metastasizes to regional lymph nodes and distant anatomic sites.

A rhabdoid tumor which arises in the soft tissues. It occurs in infants and children and may be associated with loss of chromosome 22. It is characterized by the presence of cells with a large eccentric nucleus, prominent nucleolus, and abundant cytoplasm.

The most frequent type of lymphoblastic lymphoma. It comprises approximately 85-90% of cases. It is more frequently seen in adolescent males. It frequently presents with a mass lesion in the mediastinum. Pleural effusions are common. (WHO, 2001)
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the renal pelvis.

label.value: acute myeloid leukemia with mutated NPM1

value.value: An acute myeloid leukemia with mutation of the nucleophosmin gene. It is usually associated with normal karyotype and frequently has myelomonocytic or monocytic features. It usually responds to induction therapy.

A carcinoma arising in the oral cavity. Most oral cavity carcinomas are squamous cell carcinomas of the tongue, buccal mucosa, or gums. Less frequent morphologic variants include mucoepidermoid carcinoma and adenocarcinoma.
Carcinoma, predominantly squamous cell, arising from the epithelial cells of the oropharynx.
A malignant epithelial neoplasm that arises from the rectum and invades through the muscularis mucosa into the submucosa. The vast majority are adenocarcinomas.
A rare carcinoma that arises from the paranasal sinus. It is characterized by the presence of epidermoid cells, mucus producing cells, and cells of intermediate type.
A mucoepidermoid carcinoma arising from the minor salivary glands in the oral cavity. It is often asymptomatic and detected during a routine dental examination.
A disease or disorder that involves the eosinophil.
A benign mesenchymal neoplasm composed of adipose (fatty) tissue. The most common representative of this category is the lipoma.
A disease or disorder that involves the nasolacrimal duct.
A disease or disorder that involves the lymphoid system.
A disease or disorder that involves the upper digestive tract.
A disease or disorder that involves the mouth mucosa.
A disease or disorder that involves the sympathetic nervous system.
A disease or disorder that involves the parasympathetic nervous system.
A disease or disorder that involves the cerebral cortex.
A disease or disorder that involves the midbrain.
A disease or disorder that involves the cardiac ventricle.
A disease or disorder that involves the vertebra.
A disease or disorder that involves the scrotum.
A disease or disorder that involves the skeletal ligament.

value.value: A disease that has its basis in the disruption of cholesterol metabolic process.

definition.value: Examples: disorder of cholesterol catabolism (disorder), disorder of cholesterol synthesis (disorder)

value.value: A disease that has its basis in the disruption of glycoprotein metabolic process.

definition.value: Examples: alpha-n-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency (disorder), carbohydrate-deficient glycoprotein syndrome (disorder), alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency (disorder), alpha-2-antitrypsin deficiency (disorder), sialidosis (disorder), aspartylglucosaminuria (disorder), fucosidosis (disorder), mannosidosis (disorder), i-cell disease (disorder), glycoprotein storage disorder (disorder)

value.value: A disease that has its basis in the disruption of steroid metabolic process.
A disease or disorder that involves the extraembryonic membrane.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of tetrahydrobiopterin metabolic process.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of carbohydrate transport.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of cholesterol catabolic process.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of cholesterol biosynthetic process.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of creatine biosynthetic process.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of glycine metabolic process.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of organic acid metabolic process.
An instance of adrenogenital syndrome that is acquired during the lifetime of the individual.
Any disorder that features disrupted cell proliferation. Includes hyperplasia, neoplastic syndrome and isolated neoplasm diseases as well as precancerous conditions.
